{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013nQVVx8mNiD9FjwbE2Hqj5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see that `UNION ALL BY NAME` is actually already supported! The `SetQuantifier::AllByName` is parsed in `parse_set_quantifier` (line 9663-9664). And `UNION BY NAME` as well. So UNION ALL BY NAME should already work.\n\nSo the issue is `GROUP BY ALL col_37`. Let me think about what the parser does when it sees `GROUP BY ALL col_37`:\n1. It parses `GROUP BY ALL` → `GroupByExpr::All(modifiers)`\n2. Then `col_37` comes next, and the parser tries to parse what follows GROUP BY...\n\n\n3. After consuming `GROUP BY ALL`, the parser expects to see CLUSTER BY, DISTRIBUTE BY, SORT BY, HAVING, or the closing parenthesis, but instead encounters `col_37`. The error \"Expected ), found: col_37\" suggests we're inside a parenthesized CTE where the parser thinks the GROUP BY clause is complete and is looking for the closing paren of the outer query. ...and then it stops parsing the GROUP BY clause. Now it's looking for set operators like UNION or INTERSECT, but instead it encounters `col_37`, which breaks the loop since that's not a valid set operator. The parser is still inside the subquery and expects either a closing parenthesis or another set operation, so finding `col_37` triggers the error. I think the real issue is that `GROUP BY ALL col_37` is being parsed incorrectly—`col_37` should probably be part of the GROUP BY expression, but something about how `ALL` is being handled is causing the parser to treat it as a separate token outside the GROUP BY clause. I think I see what's happening now. When `GROUP BY ALL` is parsed, the parser consumes it successfully, then returns to look for the next clause like HAVING or ORDER BY. Since `col_37` doesn't match any of those keywords, the SELECT statement parsing ends and control returns to the set operation loop. The loop doesn't recognize `col_37` as UNION/INTERSECT/EXCEPT, so it breaks and returns to the WITH clause parser, which is now expecting a comma or closing parenthesis but finds `col_37` instead—that's where the error comes from.\n\nBut the customer clearly had this working at some point, so I'm wondering if I'm misreading the SQL. Looking more carefully at `GROUP BY ALL col_37 UNION ALL BY NAME`—BigQuery's `GROUP BY ALL` treats ALL as representing all non-aggregate columns, so `col_37` after it would be unexpected. Unless this is actually MSSQL or Sybase syntax where `ALL` is a modifier that includes something specific, but that doesn't quite fit either.\n\nRather than trying to handle this edge case and risk breaking other tests, I should probably look at the simpler failures first.\n\nLet me check the \"Expected ), found: PREDICT\" error that's showing up in a couple of Snowflake customer files.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2155,"cache_read_input_tokens":87131,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2155},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6db9aadd-b916-4297-8153-a3488ed06c02","uuid":"9636273a-8b57-4ae9-9e1b-fa3aa6a5b05f"}
